        {
          "title": "Introduction to Ran's discussion on davar she-yesh lo matirin and bittul",
          "display_title": "Ran's Framework",
          "timestamp": "15:39"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Ran's conceptual framework: davar she-yesh lo matirin, min b'mino, and the nature of bittul",
      "display_title": "Davar She-Yesh Matirin",
      "timestamp": "15:46",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Davar she-yesh lo matirin: something that can or will become permissible later",
          "display_title": "Definition",
          "timestamp": "15:46"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rambam's examples: chadash (new grain) and potential application to chametz on Pesach",
          "display_title": "Rambam Examples",
          "timestamp": "16:37"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rashi's view: davar she-yesh lo matirin not batel because you can wait for it to become permitted",
          "display_title": "Rashi Position",
          "timestamp": "17:32"
        },
        {
          "title": "Mordechai's dispute: chametz has a vacillating status, not truly davar she-yesh lo matirin",
          "display_title": "Mordechai View",
          "timestamp": "18:21"
        },
        {
          "title": "Ran's alternative: davar she-yesh lo matirin relates to min b'mino; same status objects don't contradict",
          "display_title": "Ran Position",
          "timestamp": "18:55"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Contradiction between the Mishna on whey and a baraita on lentils; resolution via mar ke-atreih",
      "display_title": "Lentils Contradiction",
      "timestamp": "23:31",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Apparent contradiction: lentil flour bread (ashishim) forbidden despite transformation from lentils",
          "display_title": "Lentil Problem",
          "timestamp": "23:31"
        },
        {
          "title": "Resolution: mar ke-atreih mar ke-atreih—each follows the vernacular of their place",
          "display_title": "Mar Ke-Atreih",
          "timestamp": "24:45"
        },
        {
          "title": "In Rabbi Yose's locale, whey is called 'milk whey' so it is included in neder against milk",
          "display_title": "Milk Whey Terminology",
          "timestamp": "26:04"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Grapes, olives, and the halakhic transformation into wine and oil",
      "display_title": "Grapes & Olives",
      "timestamp": "31:17",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Neder against grapes permits wine; neder against olives permits oil—transformation creates new substances",
          "display_title": "Grapes/Olives Rule",
          "timestamp": "31:17"
        },
        {
          "title": "Wine and oil as members of the seven mashkim (liquids with halakhic significance)",
          "display_title": "Seven Mashkim",
          "timestamp": "32:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "If you say 'these grapes' or 'these olives' specifically, whatever comes out is also forbidden",
          "display_title": "These Grapes/Olives",
          "timestamp": "34:39"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rami bar Chama's question: does the prohibition depend on saying 'these' specifically or 'I will not taste'?",
          "display_title": "Rami Bar Chama Q",
          "timestamp": "35:33"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Resolution of Rami bar Chama's question via the case of fish brine (tzir)",
      "display_title": "Fish Brine Case",
      "timestamp": "43:14",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yehuda's baraita: neder applies only when 'this meat' is said and mixed with flavor-imparting items",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Yehuda Baraita",
          "timestamp": "43:14"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara cites fish case: neder against fish without saying 'these' still forbids fish, even fish brine produced afterward",
          "display_title": "Fish Mishna",
          "timestamp": "44:25"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's resolution: fish brine permitted is only brine already produced before the neder, not afterward",
          "display_title": "Rava Resolution",
          "timestamp": "45:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Conclusion: she'eini to'em ('I will not taste') is what creates the issur on yotzei mehen, not the word 'zeh'",
          "display_title": "She'eini To'em",
          "timestamp": "45:35"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Dates, date honey, and winter grapes: Rabbi Shimon ben Elazar's principle on edible vs. inedible fruits",
      "display_title": "Dates & Winter Grapes",
      "timestamp": "45:39",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Neder against dates: permitted to eat date honey; neder against date honey: forbidden from dates",
          "display_title": "Dates/Date Honey",
          "timestamp": "45:39"
        },
        {
          "title": "Nedor against winter grapes: permitted to eat vinegar made from them",
          "display_title": "Winter Grapes",
          "timestamp": "45:39"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Shimon ben Elazar's principle: things that are themselves eaten and their liquids eaten fall together in a neder",
          "display_title": "Edible Principle",
          "timestamp": "45:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "Things not normally eaten, with edible liquids: neder against them forbids only the liquid, not the fruit itself",
          "display_title": "Inedible Principle",
          "timestamp": "46:10"
        }
      ]
    }
